| FDA Considers Redefining Chocolate                                 |
|   from the this-means-war dept.                                    |
|   posted by kdawson on Monday April 23, @23:36 (The Almighty Buck) |
|   http://politics.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/04/23/2333201     |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

shewfig writes "The US Food and Drug Administration is considering
redefining 'chocolate' to allow substitution of vegetable oil ($0.70/lb.)
for cocoa butter ($2.30/lb.), and whey protein for dry whole milk. There
are already standard terms to differentiate these products from
chocolate, such as 'chocolatey' and 'chocolate-flavored.' The change was
requested by the industry group [0]Chocolate Manufacturers of America.
Leading the [1]resistance to this change is high-end chocolate maker
Guittard, with significant grass-roots support from the [2]Candyblog. The
FDA is [3]taking consumer comments until April 25. Here is the [4]FDA
page on the proposed change, which oddly enough does not say what the
proposed change is."

Discuss this story at:
    http://politics.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/04/23/2333201

Links:
    0. http://www.chocolateusa.org/About-Us/
    1. http://dontmesswithourchocolate.guittard.com/
    2. http://www.typetive.com/candyblog/
    3. http://www.accessdata.fda.gov/scripts/oc/dockets/comments/getDocketInfo.cfm?EC_DOCUMENT_ID=1477&SORT=DOCKET_NOD&MAXROWS=15&START=1&CID=&AGENCY=FDA
