+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Nanotubes May Improve Solar Energy Harvesting                      |
|   from the just-put-in-a-direct-nuclear-tap dept.                  |
|   posted by Zonk on Tuesday April 24, @12:02 (Power)               |
|   http://hardware.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/04/24/152238      |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

[0]eldavojohn writes "Scientists are hoping that the [1]'coaxial cable'
style nanotube they developed will resolve energy issues that come with
converting sunlight to energy. The [2]plants currently have us beat in
this department but research is discovering new ways to eliminate
inefficiencies in transferring photons to energy. Traditional methods
involve exciting electrons to the point of jumping to a higher state
which leaves 'holes.' Unfortunately, these electrons and holes remain in
the same regions and therefore tend to recombine. The new nanotubes hope
to route these excited electrons off in the same way a coaxial cable
allows a return route for electrons. End result is fewer electrons
settling back into their holes once they are elevated out of them
yielding a higher return in energy."

Discuss this story at:
    http://hardware.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/04/24/152238

Links:
    0. mailto:djohnsop@gmu.edu
    1. http://www.physorg.com/news96557368.html
    2. http://science.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/04/13/1240205&tid=191


+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Tech Sector Expansion Blunting U.S. Job Outsourcing                |
|   from the bringing-it-home dept.                                  |
|   posted by Zonk on Tuesday April 24, @12:39 (Businesses)          |
|   http://it.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/04/24/1532243           |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

xzvf writes "BusinessWeek summarizes a new report from the American
Electronics Association (now known as AeA) that they think [0]mitigates
the effect of outsourcing on IT employment. US demand for tech workers is
through the roof, the highest it has been since the boom of the late 90s.
The tech sector added some 150,000 new jobs 2006, and there are no signs
that interest will flag in the near future. 'There is so much global
demand for employees proficient in programming languages, engineering,
and other skills demanding higher level technology knowledge that
outsourcing can't meet all U.S. needs. "There would have been a lot more
than 147,000 jobs created here, but our companies are having difficulty
finding Americans with the background," says William Archey, president
and chief executive of the AeA. One culprit is the dearth of U.S.
engineering and computer science college graduates. Second, immigration
caps have made it difficult for highly skilled foreign-born employees to
obtain work visas. Congress has been debating whether to increase the
numbers of foreign skilled workers allowed into the country under the
H-1B visa program.' "

Discuss this story at:
    http://it.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/04/24/1532243

Links:
    0. http://www.businessweek.com/technology/content/apr2007/tc20070424_967747.htm?chan=top+news_top+news+index_top+story


